Note: ========================================
Note: x86-64 to HIR Translator
Note: ========================================
Note: Translates x86-64 Assembly AST to High-level Intermediate Representation
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Preserves instructions, operands, labels, and directives
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: AST node type constants (must match x86_parser.runa)
Constant ASM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant ASM_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 2
Constant ASM_LABEL as Integer is 3
Constant ASM_REGISTER as Integer is 4
Constant ASM_IMMEDIATE as Integer is 5
Constant ASM_MEMORY as Integer is 6
Constant ASM_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 7

@Reasoning:
The parser root collects every statement as a sibling child regardless of kind; partitioning them into typed Lists (instructions / directives / labels) at translation time lets downstream consumers index the program by kind without re-scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate the top-level Dictionary tagged type=x86_assembly. Walk the root node's children once, dispatching by tag (ASM_INSTRUCTION / ASM_DIRECTIVE / ASM_LABEL) into three pre-allocated Lists. Attach the three Lists at keys instructions / directives / labels.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in statement count; each translation call adds O(k) for its own operand subtree.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Operates on a parser-produced tree; the parser already discarded malformed statements, but consumers must still validate symbol references before linkage.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_x86_to_hir" takes asm_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point - translate x86 AST to HIR dictionary

    If asm_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set HIR document type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "x86_assembly"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Create lists for different statement types
    Let instructions be proc create from List
    Let directives be proc create from List
    Let labels be proc create from List

    Note: Process all children of root AST node
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with asm_ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        If child_type is equal to ASM_INSTRUCTION:
            Let instr_hir be proc translate_instruction with child
            If instr_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with instructions, instr_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to ASM_DIRECTIVE:
            Let dir_hir be proc translate_directive with child
            If dir_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with directives, dir_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to ASM_LABEL:
            Let label_hir be proc translate_label with child
            If label_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with labels, label_hir
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add collections to HIR
    Let instrs_key be proc create_string_literal with "instructions"
    proc set from Dict with hir, instrs_key, instructions

    Let dirs_key be proc create_string_literal with "directives"
    proc set from Dict with hir, dirs_key, directives

    Let labels_key be proc create_string_literal with "labels"
    proc set from Dict with hir, labels_key, labels

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
An instruction in HIR is "mnemonic + ordered operands"; lifting the parser's positional children into a typed operands List makes downstream lowering directly index-addressable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=instruction with the mnemonic lexeme at key "mnemonic". Iterate the instruction's children, run each through translate_operand, and push non-null results into an operands List attached at key "operands".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) in operand count.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_instruction" takes instr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate instruction node to HIR dictionary

    Let instr_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "instruction"
    proc set from Dict with instr_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract instruction mnemonic
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let mnemonic_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let mnemonic_key be proc create_string_literal with "mnemonic"
        proc set from Dict with instr_hir, mnemonic_key, mnemonic_str
    End If

    Note: Process operands
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let operands be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let operand_hir be proc translate_operand with child
        If operand_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with operands, operand_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let operands_key be proc create_string_literal with "operands"
    proc set from Dict with instr_hir, operands_key, operands

    Return instr_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Directives ".text", ".long 42", etc. share the structural shape of instructions but a distinct semantic; emitting them as type=directive with a key "name" instead of "mnemonic" lets consumers route them through the assembler-directive path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=directive with the directive lexeme at key "name". Walk the children through translate_operand and accumulate results into a List attached at key "arguments".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_directive" takes dir_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate directive node to HIR dictionary

    Let dir_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "directive"
    proc set from Dict with dir_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract directive name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with dir_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Note: Process directive arguments
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let arguments be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let arg_hir be proc translate_operand with child
        If arg_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with arguments, arg_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let args_key be proc create_string_literal with "arguments"
    proc set from Dict with dir_hir, args_key, arguments

    Return dir_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Labels are pure name-binding sites with no operands or arguments; only the name needs to survive into HIR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=label with the label lexeme attached at key "name".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_label" takes label_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate label node to HIR dictionary

    Let label_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "label"
    proc set from Dict with label_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract label name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with label_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with label_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with label_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return label_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Operands are heterogeneous (register / immediate / memory / identifier); a single dispatch helper isolates the kind-checks so caller code stays linear.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check the input. Branch on the parser node's tag: ASM_REGISTER, ASM_IMMEDIATE, ASM_MEMORY, ASM_IDENTIFIER. Unknown tags return 0 so the caller drops the operand.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_operand" takes operand_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate operand node to HIR dictionary

    If operand_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 0

    If node_type is equal to ASM_REGISTER:
        Return proc translate_register with operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ASM_IMMEDIATE:
        Return proc translate_immediate with operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ASM_MEMORY:
        Return proc translate_memory with operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ASM_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc translate_identifier with operand_node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A register operand in HIR is a discriminated leaf carrying only the register name; sub-register width is left for analysis passes that consult an ISA table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=register with the register name lexeme attached at key "name".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_register" takes reg_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate register operand to HIR

    Let reg_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "register"
    proc set from Dict with reg_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract register name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with reg_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return reg_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Immediate operands carry their literal text verbatim; numeric reinterpretation (hex, decimal, negative) belongs to later analysis once the program's data layout is known.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=immediate with the literal text lexeme attached at key "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_immediate" takes imm_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate immediate value to HIR

    Let imm_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "immediate"
    proc set from Dict with imm_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract immediate value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with imm_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with imm_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let value_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
        proc set from Dict with imm_hir, value_key, value_str
    End If

    Return imm_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser stores memory-operand components positionally (offset, base, index, scale) and the first-child type disambiguates which slots are present: starting with IMMEDIATE or IDENTIFIER means an offset is present and base shifts to position 1; otherwise the first slot is the base register.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=memory. Inspect children[0]'s tag. If ASM_IMMEDIATE: children index sequence is offset / base / index / scale. If ASM_IDENTIFIER: same shape (offset is a symbolic offset). Otherwise (parser already emitted base register first): children index sequence is base / index / scale. Each present slot is converted via get_operand_value_string and attached at the appropriate key.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - bounded by the at-most four-component memory operand shape.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_memory" takes mem_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate memory reference to HIR

    Let mem_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "memory"
    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process memory reference components (offset, base, index, scale)
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Note: Parse components in order: offset, base, index, scale
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with first_child, 0

        Note: First child can be offset or base register
        If first_type is equal to ASM_IMMEDIATE:
            Let offset_str be proc get_operand_value_string with first_child
            Let offset_key be proc create_string_literal with "offset"
            proc set from Dict with mem_hir, offset_key, offset_str

            Note: Check for base register
            If child_count is greater than 1:
                Let base_child_a be proc get from List with children, 1
                Let base_str_a be proc get_operand_value_string with base_child_a
                Let base_key_a be proc create_string_literal with "base"
                proc set from Dict with mem_hir, base_key_a, base_str_a
            End If

            Note: Check for index register
            If child_count is greater than 2:
                Let index_child_a be proc get from List with children, 2
                Let index_str_a be proc get_operand_value_string with index_child_a
                Let index_key_a be proc create_string_literal with "index"
                proc set from Dict with mem_hir, index_key_a, index_str_a
            End If

            Note: Check for scale
            If child_count is greater than 3:
                Let scale_child_a be proc get from List with children, 3
                Let scale_str_a be proc get_operand_value_string with scale_child_a
                Let scale_key_a be proc create_string_literal with "scale"
                proc set from Dict with mem_hir, scale_key_a, scale_str_a
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If first_type is equal to ASM_IDENTIFIER:
                Let offset_str_b be proc get_operand_value_string with first_child
                Let offset_key_b be proc create_string_literal with "offset"
                proc set from Dict with mem_hir, offset_key_b, offset_str_b

                Note: Check for base register
                If child_count is greater than 1:
                    Let base_child_b be proc get from List with children, 1
                    Let base_str_b be proc get_operand_value_string with base_child_b
                    Let base_key_b be proc create_string_literal with "base"
                    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, base_key_b, base_str_b
                End If

                Note: Check for index register
                If child_count is greater than 2:
                    Let index_child_b be proc get from List with children, 2
                    Let index_str_b be proc get_operand_value_string with index_child_b
                    Let index_key_b be proc create_string_literal with "index"
                    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, index_key_b, index_str_b
                End If

                Note: Check for scale
                If child_count is greater than 3:
                    Let scale_child_b be proc get from List with children, 3
                    Let scale_str_b be proc get_operand_value_string with scale_child_b
                    Let scale_key_b be proc create_string_literal with "scale"
                    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, scale_key_b, scale_str_b
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: First is base register (no offset)
                Let base_str_c be proc get_operand_value_string with first_child
                Let base_key_c be proc create_string_literal with "base"
                proc set from Dict with mem_hir, base_key_c, base_str_c

                Note: Check for index register
                If child_count is greater than 1:
                    Let index_child_c be proc get from List with children, 1
                    Let index_str_c be proc get_operand_value_string with index_child_c
                    Let index_key_c be proc create_string_literal with "index"
                    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, index_key_c, index_str_c
                End If

                Note: Check for scale
                If child_count is greater than 2:
                    Let scale_child_c be proc get from List with children, 2
                    Let scale_str_c be proc get_operand_value_string with scale_child_c
                    Let scale_key_c be proc create_string_literal with "scale"
                    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, scale_key_c, scale_str_c
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return mem_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier operands - branch targets, GOT references, directive arguments - are deferred symbolic references whose linkage resolution happens after translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=identifier with the identifier lexeme attached at key "name".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_identifier" takes ident_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate identifier (symbol) to HIR

    Let ident_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "identifier"
    proc set from Dict with ident_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract identifier name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ident_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ident_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with ident_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return ident_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The memory-operand translator needs raw value strings (not full Dictionary wrappers) for each component; a single helper keeps the lexeme-to-String conversion in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the node's value pointer and length. If length is non-zero, materialise a String from the buffer. Otherwise return an empty String literal so callers can safely store the key without checking for null.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_operand_value_string" takes operand_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract value string from operand node

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
    End If
    Return proc create_string_literal with ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-literal construction is wrapped so that future intern-table or arena-string changes touch only one call site instead of every key creation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_string_from_literal and return its pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process
